Part II - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration and Visualization¶

by Wejdan Al-Qahtani¶

Investigation Overview¶

In the San Francisco Bay Area of California, Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing scheme. Bay Area Bike Share, a pilot program for the region, started in August 2013 with 700 bikes and 70 stations dispersed around San Francisco and San Jose. The Ford GoBike system presently has more than 2,600 bicycles spread out among 262 stations in San Francisco, the East Bay, and San Jose. On June 28, 2017, the program was formally unveiled as Ford GoBike in collaboration with Ford Motor Company.¶

The Ford GoBike bike share program uses a fleet of strong, well-made bikes that are locked into a system of docking stations spread out over the city. The bike is perfect for one-way travels because you may unlock it at one station and return it to any other station in the network. Additionally, the bikes are always ready for use, and anyone can use any bike in the network provided they join or buy a pass.¶

Dataset Overview¶

The monthly individual trip data for the larger San Francisco Bay area in CSV format from January 2019 to December 2019 comprise the dataset used for this exploratory investigation. The visualizations below were made using wrangled and cleaned data to simplify analysis, find usage patterns, and identify riders characteristics.

User Types and Their Weekly Usage¶

In 2019, subscribers used bicycles 89 percent of the time, while customers used bicycles 11 percent of the time . When there are more subscribers, both subscribers and customers ride the Throughout all weeks in February. 

Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Customers and Subscribers¶

It is obvious that the two types of riders have different usage patterns and behaviors. On weekdays, Monday through Friday, subscribers made heavy use of the system, although weekend ridership was higher, especially in the afternoon. When utilized for commuting, subscribers made a lot of journeys between 8 and 9 am and 17 to 18 pm on weekdays. However, non-subscribers tended to make more trips between 17 and 18 pm, Monday through Friday.

Average Weekday Trip Duration for Customers and Subscribers¶

The bellow graphic shows that on every day of the week, subscribers take shorter/quicker trips than non-subscribers. On Saturdays and Sundays, both user categories' trip lengths clearly rise compared to weekends, notably for casual riders. Monday through Friday, subscribers' usage had a fairly steady average length and appeared to be more effective than customers overall.

The relationship between the various variables plotted is seen collectively and information is displayed simultaneously, strengthening some of the patterns identified in the preceding bivariate investigation as well as in the univariate research. Subscribers' efficient/short periods of consumption are consistent with their high concentration during Monday through Friday rush hours, showing that the use is mostly for commuting to work. Customers clearly utilize the bike sharing system considerably differently than subscribers, frequently on weekends and in the afternoons, likely for leisure or city tours, as seen by the more flexible and relaxing pattern of their usage.
